{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb400 
I. BACKGROUND
\par 
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Since 1978, Yale Law School (\u8220\'3fYLS\u8221\'3f) has prohibited discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation. Yale\rquote s Nondiscrimination Policy (\u8220\'3fNDP\u8221\'3f), which applies to all aspects of YLS life, provides:
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb200 
Yale Law School is committed to a policy against discrimination based upon age, color, handicap or disability, ethnic or national origin, race, religion, religious creed, gender (including discrimination taking the form of sexual harassment), marital, parental or veteran status, sexual orientation, or the prejudice of clients. All employers using the school\rquote s placement services are required to abide by this policy.
\par 
}
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Employers who refuse to certify their compliance with the NDP are barred from school-sponsored recruiting services. Compl. at \u182\'3f 2, 17.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In light of the military\rquote s regulations regarding gay and lesbian service members, popularly known as the \u8220\'3fDon\rquote t Ask Don\rquote t Tell\u8221\'3f policy, the Department of Defense has refused to certify its compliance with the Law School\rquote s NDP and has thus been denied the use of YLS\rquote s Career Development Office (\u8220\'3fCDO\u8221\'3f) since 1978. Compl. at \u182\'3f 28. Instead, the law school has offered military recruiters open access to classrooms and other meeting spaces on campus for informational sessions and other recruiting activities, including interviews, at the invitation of a student organization; open access to any student or student group to reserve a classroom or other meeting space for such a meeting at any time; and open access to student contact information.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In 1995, in light of policies like the YLS NDP, and related controversies over the presence of ROTC programs on university campuses, Congress enacted the Solomon Amendment, now codified at 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000546&cite=10USCAS983&originatingDoc=I36146db1542211d997e0acd5cbb90d3f&refType=LQ&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.UserEnteredCitation)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
10 U.S.C. \u167\'3f 983
}}}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. Among other things, the Solomon Amendment denies certain categories of federal funding to institutions of higher education that prevent military recruitment on campus. The Amendment in its current form provides:
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
(b) Denial of funds for preventing military recruiting on campus
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb200 
.\u8212\'3fNo funds described in subsection (d)(2) may be provided by contract or by grant (including a grant of funds to be available for student aid) to an institution of higher education (including any subelement of such institution) if the Secretary of Defense determines that that institution (or any subelement of that institution) has a policy or practice (regardless of when implemented) that either prohibits, or in effect prevents\u8212\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb200 
(1) the Secretary of a military department or Secretary of Homeland Security from gaining entry to campuses, or access to students (who are 17 years of age or older) on campuses, for purposes of military recruiting; or
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_4637_194_3}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_4637_194_3}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*194
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb200 
 (2) access by military recruiters for purposes of military recruiting to the following information pertaining to students (who are 17 years of age or older) enrolled at that institution (or any subelement of that institution):
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb200 
(A) Names, addresses, and telephone listings.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li200 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb200 
(B) Date and place of birth, levels of education, academic majors, degrees received, and the most recent educational institution enrolled in by the student.
\par 
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The Department of Defense\rquote s original interpretive regulations limited loss of funding to the particular part of the university (\u8220\'3fsubelement\u8221\'3f) found not to be in compliance. In other words, if a subelement of a university, like a law school, denied access to military recruiters, then only that subelement would lose funding, not the entire institution. 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
See
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=l&pubNum=0001037&cite=UUID(I593159203CE311DAAECA8D28B8108CB8)&originatingDoc=I36146db1542211d997e0acd5cbb90d3f&refType=CP&fi=co_pp_sp_1037_7739&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.UserEnteredCitation)#co_pp_sp_1037_7739" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
61 Fed.Reg. 7739, 7740 (Feb. 29, 1996)
}}}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. Further, the Amendment initially implicated only Department of Defense (\u8220\'3fDoD\u8221\'3f) funding. Because law schools, unlike other segments of a university, are not recipients of large amounts of DoD funds, the Amendment in its initial form apparently provided little leverage to encourage law schools to change their recruiting policies.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In 1997, Congress extended the rule denying federal funds to apply to grants and contracts provided by the Departments of Labor, Health and Human Services, Education, and Transportation, as well as Defense. 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=l&pubNum=1077005&cite=UUID(I747341D64B-9E4A43B3D8A-975AE78FBD0)&originatingDoc=I36146db1542211d997e0acd5cbb90d3f&refType=SL&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.UserEnteredCitation)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Pub.L. No. 104\u8211\'3f208, 110 Stat. 3009 (1996)
}}}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, codified at 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000546&cite=10USCAS983&originatingDoc=I36146db1542211d997e0acd5cbb90d3f&refType=LQ&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.UserEnteredCitation)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
10 U.S.C. \u167\'3f 983
}}}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. This extension threatened certain types of student aid, including Perkins Loans and work study funds. However, the applicable regulations continued to cabin the consequences of a subelement\rquote s failure to grant access to military recruiters to that subelement itself, such that non-compliance did not affect the larger university.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In the fall of 1999, Congress enacted further changes to the Amendment, this time to protect students of non-compliant university subelements by exempting funds \u8220\'3favailable solely for student financial assistance or related administrative costs.\u8221\'3f Department of Defense Appropriations Act of 2000, 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=l&pubNum=1077005&cite=UUID(I7176A0E9B8-434B30BE8A3-5D57184A1C7)&originatingDoc=I36146db1542211d997e0acd5cbb90d3f&refType=SL&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.UserEnteredCitation)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Pub.L. No. 106\u8211\'3f79, 113 Stat. 1212 (1999).
}}}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Congress also modified the statute\rquote s language to specifically apply to any \u8220\'3finstitution of higher education (including any subelement of such institution).\u8221\'3f 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000546&cite=10USCAS983&originatingDoc=I36146db1542211d997e0acd5cbb90d3f&refType=RB&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.UserEnteredCitation)#co_pp_fcf30000ea9c4" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
10 U.S.C. \u167\'3f 983(c)(2)
}}}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
, as modified by 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=l&pubNum=1077005&cite=UUID(I6CB5DA89FE-764754911D8-FF663B16F93)&originatingDoc=I36146db1542211d997e0acd5cbb90d3f&refType=SL&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.UserEnteredCitation)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Pub.L. No. 106\u8211\'3f65, \u167\'3f 549(a)(1) 
}}}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
(1999).
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
After this change, the DoD adopted interim regulations, effective immediately, that defined an \u8220\'3finstitution of higher education\u8221\'3f to include 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u8220\'3fall sub-elements of such an institution.\u8221\'3f Defense Federal Acquisition Regulation Supplement: Institutions of Higher Education. 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=0113454217&pubNum=1037&originatingDoc=I36146db1542211d997e0acd5cbb90d3f&refType=FR&fi=co_pp_sp_1037_2056&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.UserEnteredCitation)#co_pp_sp_1037_2056" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
65 Fed.Reg.2056 (Jan. 13, 2000)
}}}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. The effect of this redefinition imputed a subelement\rquote s violation to the entire university, such that a violation in any part of the university would put the funding of the whole university in jeopardy. 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000547&cite=48CFR252.209-7005&originatingDoc=I36146db1542211d997e0acd5cbb90d3f&refType=LQ&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.UserEnteredCitation)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf20 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
48 C.F.R. \u167\'3f 252.209\u8211\'3f7005
}}}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The DoD also extended the plain text of the Amendment in another way. Though the Amendment itself speaks only to schools that \u8220\'3fin effect, prevent\u8221\'3f military recruiting on campus, the DoD promulgated regulations requiring access \u8220\'3fat least equal in quality and scope\u8221\'3f to that afforded to other employers, if not identical. 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=L&pubNum=1000547&cite=32CFRS216.4&originatingDoc=I36146db1542211d997e0acd5cbb90d3f&refType=RB&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.UserEnteredCitation)#co_pp_4b24000003ba5" }{\fldrslt 
