The current conflict between YLS and the DoD began with a several-year-long series of administrative exchanges between YLS staff and various military recruiting officers regarding the NDP. On December 17, 2001, Colonel Clyde J. Tate, III, U.S. Army, advised Yale University President Richard Levin, \u8220\'3fI understand that military recruiting personnel have been inappropriately limited in their ability to recruit or have been refused student recruiting information at Yale University by a policy or practice of the Yale Law School.\u8221\'3f Colonel Tate advised Levin that \u8220\'3fcurrent statutes deny the use of certain federal funds\u8221\'3f to institutions of higher education with a policy or practice of denying military recruiting personnel entry to campuses, and stated, \u8220\'3f[t]his letter provides you an opportunity to clarify your institution\rquote s policy regarding military recruiting on the campus of Yale University as well as Yale Law School.\u8221\'3f 
